{
  "text": "The ability of an adult to recognize the sex of an immature is a prerequisite to manipulating the sex ratio for maximizing inclusive fitness. However, to our knowledge, no report has confirmed that adults can discriminate sex at the egg stage [CITATION_1] . This lack of evidence for egg sexing leads us to suggest that adults of social insects can discriminate the sex of an immature only after egg hatching. Moreover, many researchers have reported that a queen's eggs are chemically marked (e.g. [CITATION_2] . These findings suggest that adults of social insects might recognize the odour marking on eggs, signalling the identity of queen-laid eggs, but might not discriminate the sex of eggs [CITATION_3] . If a queen marks her eggs and workers can recognize the odour, upon every replacement, they should favour the removal of eggs destined to be nephews, avoiding the high cost of destroying queen-laid female eggs (sexual-deception hypothesis; [CITATION_4] . In one of our study colonies (1019), workers removed only fellow workers' eggs. This result suggests that, albeit that variation between colonies Number of larvae (%) are those where we successfully constructed mother-offspring relationships using microsatellite genotypings. We calculate Fisher's combined probability, which revealed a significant difference from parity ( p < 0.01).",
